## Confirming the duplication

`crimes scan --format json` returns a single `near_duplicate_block` finding (`crime_00001`, medium severity, confidence 0.85) with hash `289f7da71f3a…` appearing in 3 files / 3 occurrences:

- `src/sanitize-a.ts:2-28` — `sanitizeUserInput(raw: string)`
- `src/sanitize-b.ts:2-28` — `sanitizeText(input: string)`
- `src/sanitize-c.ts:2-28` — `cleanMessage(value: string)`

Reading the bodies confirms they are byte-for-byte identical aside from parameter/local-variable renames (`raw/working`, `input/cleaned`, `value/normalised`). Same `trim → strip control chars → collapse whitespace → 1000-char cap → leading-angle-bracket reject → \x reject → punctuation-spam reject → all-caps downcase` pipeline.

## Proposed refactor

Extract one shared helper into a new `src/sanitize.ts` and have the three existing modules re-export from it. Grepping the fixture finds zero call sites for any of the three original names, so this can be done as a pure consolidation — no caller updates needed inside the fixture (downstream callers in a real repo would keep working via the re-exports).

**Files that would change:**

| File | Change |
|---|---|
| `src/sanitize.ts` *(new)* | Holds the single implementation. |
| `src/sanitize-a.ts` | Body deleted; re-export `sanitizeUserInput` as an alias of the shared helper. |
| `src/sanitize-b.ts` | Same — alias `sanitizeText`. |
| `src/sanitize-c.ts` | Same — alias `cleanMessage`. |

If callers do exist outside the fixture, the aliases preserve the public surface; once they're migrated the three shim files can be deleted in a follow-up.

## Public API of the consolidated function

```ts
// src/sanitize.ts

export interface SanitizeOptions {
  /** Hard cap on output length after whitespace collapse. Default 1000. */
  maxLength?: number;
  /** Reject (return "") when input starts with "<" or ">". Default true. */
  rejectAngleBrackets?: boolean;
  /** Reject (return "") when input contains a literal "\x" escape. Default true. */
  rejectHexEscapes?: boolean;
  /** Reject (return "") when run of !/? of length ≥3 appears >N times. Default 5. */
  maxPunctuationRuns?: number;
  /**
   * If the uppercase-letter ratio exceeds this and the string is longer
   * than `shoutMinLength`, lowercase the output. Default 0.9 / 30.
   */
  shoutRatio?: number;
  shoutMinLength?: number;
}

/**
 * Normalise and validate untrusted user text.
 * Returns "" for null/undefined or any input that fails a reject rule.
 */
export function sanitize(input: string | null | undefined, opts?: SanitizeOptions): string;
```

Defaults exactly reproduce the current behaviour, so the three callers become one-liners:

```ts
// src/sanitize-a.ts
export { sanitize as sanitizeUserInput } from "./sanitize";
// src/sanitize-b.ts
export { sanitize as sanitizeText } from "./sanitize";
// src/sanitize-c.ts
export { sanitize as cleanMessage } from "./sanitize";
```

Rationale for the options object rather than a bare `(s: string) => string`: the magic numbers (`1000`, `5`, `0.9`, `30`) and the reject rules are the bits most likely to need per-call-site tuning once this is shared — surfacing them as options means future divergence happens through configuration, not by copy-pasting the body again. The current behaviour stays the zero-arg default so the consolidation itself is a no-op refactor.
